IAstArrayMapExpression.description:
`Array.map()` function expression.

`IAstArrayMapExpression` is an interface that visualizes the `Array.map()`
function, which transforms the original array into another type of array.

{@link expression} and {@link transformer} represent the target array and
the transformation expression, respectively, and {@link id} is used to identify
individual (parameter) elements and index numbers of the callback function that
`Array.map()` will use. Specifically, it exists for the callback function's
parameter {@link IAstArrayFunctionParameterIdentifier.expression_id} that
refers to individual elements in `Array.map((element, index) => ...)` and
{@link IAstArrayFunctionIndexIdentifier.expression_id} that visualizes
the index numbers.

Below is an example of using `IAstArrayMapExpression`.

### Code example
```typescript const array: number[] = [...];
array.map((value, index) => {
  return {
    id: value + index,
    age: 20,
  };
});
```

### Expression
```typescript
{
  type: "ArrayMapExpression",
  id: "some_map_expression_id",
  expression: { type: "Identifier", text: "array" },
  transformer: {
    type: "ObjectLiteralExpression",
    properties: [
      {
        type: "PropertyAssignment",
        name: { type: "Identifier", text: "id" },
        initializer: {
          type: "BinaryExpression",
          left: {
            type: "ArrayFunctionParameterIdentifier",
            expression_id: "some_map_expression_id",
            index: 0,
          },
          operator: "+",
          right: {
            type: "ArrayFunctionIndexIdentifier",
            expression_id: "some_map_expression_id",
          },
        },
      },
      {
        type: "PropertyAssignment",
        name: { type: "Identifier", text: "age" },
        initializer: { type: "NumericLiteral", text: "20" },
      },
    ],
  },
}
```

IAstObjectEntriesExpression.description:
`Object.entries()` expression.

An expression that returns all key value values of an object as an array.

However, unlike JS's own `Object.entries()`, it is returned as an object
type, not a tuple type of key values, as follows.

```typescript
Object.entries(obj).map(
  ([key, value]) => ({
    key,
    value,
  })
);
```

IAstWorkflowParameterIdentifier.description:
Workflow parameter identifier expression.

{@link IStudioWorkflow workflow document} is also conceptually expressed as a
function, and accordingly, can have {@link IStudioWorkflowParameter own parameter}.
And `IAstWorkflowParameterIdentifier` is an expression that identifies the
parameter of the workflow document among the nodes placed in the workflow document.

That is, `IAstWorkflowParameterIdentifier` is a type of {@link IAstIdentifier},

but is a dedicated identifier expression for workflow parameters only.

```typescript
export namespace Workflow {
  export function main(p0: number, p1: number) {
    p0; // { type: "WorkflowParameterIdentifier", index: 0 }
    p1; // { type: "WorkflowParameterIdentifier", index: 1 }
  }
}
```

IAstWorkflowLoopStatementResultIdentifie.description:
An identifier expression for the return value of a workflow Loop statement.

In the {@link IStudioWorkflow workflow document}, if a loop such as
{@link IStudioWorkflowForEachStatement} or {@link IStudioWorkflowWhileStatement}
is used, all {@link IAstWorkflowCallStatementResultIdentifier local variables}
generated by {@link IStudioWorkflowCallStatement connector function call}, etc.,
within the loop block, are inserted into the array declared before the start of
the loop block.

> However, if {@link IStudioWorkflowBreakStatement break} or
> {@link IStudioWorkflowContinueStatement continue} statements are used within
> the loop, local variables are not inserted into the array.

`IAstWorkflowLoopStatementResultIdentifier` is an expression that identifies
the array containing the local variables generated in this loop. That is,
`IAstWorkflowLoopStatementResultIdentifier` is a type of {@link IAstIdentifier},
but it is a dedicated identifier expression for the loop result array.

Of course, even if the loop is used double or triple, the array variable pointed
to by `IAstWorkflowLoopStatementResultIdentifier` is also inserted into the
array of the upper loop statement.

If you do not understand the above, look at the example code below. The `pointers`
variable in the example code below is the object pointed to by this
`IAstWorkflowLoopStatementResultIdentifier`.

```typescript
interface Pointer {
  x: number;
  y: number;
  z: number;
}
const pointers: Pointer[] = [];

for (let i: number = 0; i < 10; ++i) {
  // Call three connector functions within the For loop
  const x: number = computeX(i); const y: number = computeY(i);
  const z: number = computeZ(i);

  // Not applicable if continue or break node exists
  if (x === y && y === z) continue;
  else if (x < 0) break;

  // When the For loop block ends,
  // Store all created local variables in an array
  pointers.push({ x, y, z });
}

// And can be used outside the For loop
const emended: IPointer[] = emendPointers(pointers);
```

IAstShorthandPropertyAssignment.description:
Shorthand property assignment.

An expression that uses the variable name as a property name by opening
only the variable name, and also assigns the value at the same time.

```typescript
const value = "shorthand";
const x = {
  value,
  other: "something";
}
```

IAstSpreadAssignment.description:
Spread properties assignment.

```typescript
const x = { value: 1 };
const y = {
  something: "nothing",
  ...x,
}
```

IStudioWorkflowReturnStatement.description:
Node to return during workflow execution.

```typescript
return;
return <expr>;
```

This statement stops execution immediately, so you cannot specify the next node.

IStudioWorkflowContinueStatement.description:
Continue node that immediately restarts the loop in the workflow.

`IStudioWorkflowContinueStatement` is a node entity that visualizes the
Continue statement that immediately restarts the loop in the
{@link IStudioWorkflowWorkflow program} {@link IStudioWorkflowForEachStatement}
or {@link IStudioWorkflowWhilteStatement}

It can only be used in the loops of the above entities. And if local variables
are created in the original loop, such as
{@link IStudioWorkflowCallStatement connector function call}, they are all
inserted into the array declared before the start of the loop block. However,
if the `IStudioWorkflowContinueStatement` or
{@link IStudioWorkflowBreakStatement break} statement is used in the loop, the
local variables are not inserted into the upper array.

```typescript
const array = [];
for (const elem of array) {
  ...(some-statements)
  continue;
  array.push({ ...variables generated in the block });
}
```

